  argTypes: {
    label: { control: 'text' },
    placeholder: { control: 'text' },
    value: { control: 'text' },
    onChange: { action: 'changed' },
    disabled: { control: 'boolean' },
    error: { control: 'text' },
    required: { control: 'boolean' },
  },
};

// Default story
export const Default = {
  args: {
    label: 'Default Text Field',
    placeholder: 'Enter text here',
  },
};

// With Error
export const WithError = {
  args: {
    label: 'Error Text Field',
    placeholder: 'Enter text here',
    error: 'This field is required',
  },
};

// Disabled
export const Disabled = {
  args: {
    label: 'Disabled Text Field',
    placeholder: 'Enter text here',
    disabled: true,
  },
};

// Required
export const Required = {
  args: {
    label: 'Required Text Field',
    placeholder: 'Enter text here',
    required: true,
  },
};
```

This stories file:
1. Creates different variations of your TextField component
2. Allows control of props through Storybook's controls panel
3. Includes common use cases (default, with error, disabled, required)
4. Uses the new Component Story Format (CSF)

To use this:
1. Place it in the same directory as your TextField component
2. Name it `TextField.stories.tsx` (or `.jsx` for JavaScript)
3. Make sure your Storybook configuration is properly set up
4. Your TextField stories should appear in Storybook under the "Components" section

You might need to adjust the props and stories based on your actual TextField component's implementation and requirements.

