How can I add a very basic loading animation on clicked buttons?

Here are a few simple ways to add loading animations to buttons:

1. Simple Spinner using CSS:
```css
.button-spinner {
  animation: spin 1s linear infinite;
  border: 2px solid #f3f3f3;
  border-top: 2px solid #3498db;
  border-radius: 50%;
  width: 16px;
  height: 16px;
  display: inline-block;
}

@keyframes spin {
  0% { transform: rotate(0deg); }
  100% { transform: rotate(360deg); }
}
```

```jsx
function Button({ loading, children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button disabled={loading} {...props}>
      {loading ? <span className="button-spinner" /> : children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

2. Using dots animation:
```css
.loading-dots::after {
  content: '.';
  animation: dots 1.5s steps(5, end) infinite;
}

@keyframes dots {
  0%, 20% { content: '.'; }
  40% { content: '..'; }
  60% { content: '...'; }
  80%, 100% { content: ''; }
}
```

```jsx
function Button({ loading, children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button disabled={loading} {...props}>
      {loading ? <span className="loading-dots">Loading</span> : children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

3. Simple text fade animation:
```css
.button-loading {
  opacity: 0.7;
  animation: pulse 1s infinite;
}

@keyframes pulse {
  0% { opacity: 0.7; }
  50% { opacity: 0.4; }
  100% { opacity: 0.7; }
}
```

```jsx
function Button({ loading, children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button 
      disabled={loading} 
      className={loading ? 'button-loading' : ''}
      {...props}
    >
      {loading ? 'Loading...' : children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

4. Using SVG spinner:
```jsx
function LoadingSpinner() {
  return (
    <svg 
      width="16" 
      height="16" 
      viewBox="0 0 24 24" 
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
    >
      <style>
        {`
          .spinner {
            animation: rotate 2s linear infinite;
            transform-origin: center;
          }
          .spinner-path {
            animation: dash 1.5s ease-in-out infinite;
          }
          @keyframes rotate {
            100% {
              transform: rotate(360deg);
            }
          }
          @keyframes dash {
            0% {
              stroke-dasharray: 1, 150;
              stroke-dashoffset: 0;
            }
            50% {
              stroke-dasharray: 90, 150;
              stroke-dashoffset: -35;
            }
            100% {
              stroke-dasharray: 90, 150;
              stroke-dashoffset: -124;
            }
          }
        `}
      </style>
      <circle
        className="spinner-path"
        cx="12"
        cy="12"
        r="10"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        strokeWidth="2"
      />
    </svg>
  );
}

function Button({ loading, children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button disabled={loading} {...props}>
      {loading ? <LoadingSpinner /> : children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

5. Using a library like react-spinners:
```jsx
import ClipLoader from "react-spinners/ClipLoader";

function Button({ loading, children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button disabled={loading} {...props}>
      {loading ? (
        <ClipLoader size={15} color={"#ffffff"} loading={loading} />
      ) : (
        children
      )}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Usage example:
```jsx
function App() {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  const handleClick = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    // Simulate API call
    await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 2000));
    setLoading(false);
  };

  return (
    <Button loading={loading} onClick={handleClick}>
      Click Me
    </Button>
  );
}
```

Styling example:
```css
button {
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 4px;
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: white;
  cursor: pointer;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  min-width: 100px;
  min-height: 40px;
}

button:disabled {
  cursor: not-allowed;
  opacity: 0.7;
}
```

These examples provide different ways to show loading states. Choose the one that best matches your design needs. The key points are:
1. Disable the button when loading
2. Show a visual indicator that something is happening
3. Make sure the button size doesn't change dramatically when switching states
how can I implement the ability to choose whether or not the button, of any variant and size can have a icon either to the right or the left of the text?
Here's how you can implement a flexible button component with optional icons on either side:

```tsx
// Button.tsx
import React, { ReactNode } from 'react';

interface ButtonProps {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'outline';
  size?: 'small' | 'medium' | 'large';
  leftIcon?: ReactNode;
  rightIcon?: ReactNode;
  children: ReactNode;
  loading?: boolean;
  onClick?: () => void;
  disabled?: boolean;
  className?: string;
}

const Button = ({
  variant = 'primary',
  size = 'medium',
  leftIcon,
  rightIcon,
  children,
  loading,
  onClick,
  disabled,
  className,
  ...props
}: ButtonProps) => {
  return (
    <button
      className={`
        button 
        button--${variant} 
        button--${size}
        ${loading ? 'button--loading' : ''}
        ${className || ''}
      `}
      disabled={disabled || loading}
      onClick={onClick}
      {...props}
    >
      {loading ? (
        <span className="button-spinner" />
      ) : (
        <>
          {leftIcon && <span className="button__icon button__icon--left">{leftIcon}</span>}
          <span className="button__text">{children}</span>
          {rightIcon && <span className="button__icon button__icon--right">{rightIcon}</span>}
        </>
      )}
    </button>
  );
};

export default Button;
```

```css
/* Button.css */
.button {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  gap: 8px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 4px;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: all 0.2s;
}

/* Size variants */
.button--small {
  padding: 6px 12px;
  font-size: 14px;
}

.button--medium {
  padding: 8px 16px;
  font-size: 16px;
}

.button--large {
  padding: 12px 24px;
  font-size: 18px;
}

/* Style variants */
.button--primary {
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: white;
}

.button--secondary {
  background-color: #6c757d;
  color: white;
}

.button--outline {
  background-color: transparent;
  border: 1px solid #007bff;
  color: #007bff;
}

/* Icon styling */
.button__icon {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
}

.button__icon--left {
  margin-right: 4px;
}

.button__icon--right {
  margin-left: 4px;
}

/* Disabled state */
.button:disabled {
  opacity: 0.7;
  cursor: not-allowed;
}

/* Loading spinner */
.button-spinner {
  /* Add your spinner styling here */
}
```

Usage examples:

```jsx
import { FiArrowRight, FiDownload, FiPlus } from 'react-icons/fi'; // Using react-icons as an example

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* Button with left icon */}
      <Button leftIcon={<FiPlus />}>
        Add Item
      </Button>

      {/* Button with right icon */}
      <Button rightIcon={<FiArrowRight />}>
        Next
      </Button>

      {/* Button with both icons */}
      <Button 
        leftIcon={<FiDownload />} 
        rightIcon={<FiArrowRight />}
        variant="secondary"
        size="large"
      >
        Download Report
      </Button>

      {/* Different variants */}
      <Button variant="primary" leftIcon={<FiPlus />}>
        Primary
      </Button>

      <Button variant="secondary" rightIcon={<FiArrowRight />}>
        Secondary
      </Button>

      <Button variant="outline" leftIcon={<FiDownload />}>
        Outline
      </Button>

      {/* Different sizes */}
      <Button size="small" leftIcon={<FiPlus />}>
        Small
      </Button>

      <Button size="medium" leftIcon={<FiPlus />}>
        Medium
      </Button>

      <Button size="large" leftIcon={<FiPlus />}>
        Large
      </Button>

      {/* Loading state */}
      <Button loading>
        Loading
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

For Storybook:

```tsx
// Button.stories.tsx
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from '@storybook/react';
import Button from './Button';
import { FiArrowRight, FiDownload, FiPlus } from 'react-icons/fi';

const meta: Meta<typeof Button> = {
  title: 'Components/Button',
  component: Button,
  argTypes: {
    variant: {
      control: 'select',
      options: ['primary', 'secondary', 'outline'],
    },
    size: {
      control: 'select',
      options: ['small', 'medium', 'large'],
    },
    loading: {
      control: 'boolean',
    },
    disabled: {
      control: 'boolean',
    },
  },
};

export default meta;
type Story = StoryObj<typeof Button>;

export const Default: Story = {
  args: {
    children: 'Button',
  },
};

export const WithLeftIcon: Story = {
  args: {
    children: 'Add Item',
    leftIcon: <FiPlus />,
  },
};

export const WithRightIcon: Story = {
  args: {
    children: 'Next',
    rightIcon: <FiArrowRight />,
  },
};

export const WithBothIcons: Story = {
  args: {
    children: 'Download Report',
    leftIcon: <FiDownload />,
    rightIcon: <FiArrowRight />,
  },
};

export const Loading: Story = {
  args: {
    children: 'Loading',
    loading: true,
  },
};
```

This implementation:
1. Allows for icons on either or both sides
2. Supports different button variants and sizes
3. Maintains consistent spacing
4. Handles loading states
5. Is fully typed with TypeScript
6. Includes Storybook stories for documentation
7. Uses CSS classes for styling (you could also use CSS-in-JS or other styling solutions)
8. Is flexible enough to work with any icon library or custom icons

You can further customize the styling, add more variants, or adjust the spacing between icons and text by modifying the CSS.
